posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com: Marquee Moon is odd. It feels simultaneously familiar and unique at once, but close listening reveals an album that seems wholly unaware of the musical traditions of guitar music which had sedimented around the time of its release in 1977. It's the guitars on this album which stimulates most discussion. Guitarists Lloyd and Verlaine render familiar distinctions such as rhythm and lead obsolete, switching places as they see fit, there's almost a complete absence of distortion yet the songs still rock, but most surprisingly Verlaine's style (apparently) makes use of the familiar pentatonic scales but there's not a blues lick in sight. The album doesn't celebrate musical heritage nor seek to undermine it like their less musically refined punk contemporaries, it's just there, separate from it, which is bizarrely admirable.

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
>>114811009
MP3 is usually 320kbps, which is great, it's what you want. It's not lossless but it's not heavy and the quality is sufficient to appreciate all the details in the music.
WAV is a professional format, it's lossless because it's the pure rendition of what appears in a DAW. It's lossless because it's raw audio but it's basically useless: it's too heavy, it doesn't allow metadata (I believe). You don't want to listen to WAV files.
FLAC is a lossless audio format made to listen to music. It allows metadata and you can play it in your media player if it has the appropriate codec. It's up to 70% less heavy than WAV but the sound is the same. Now, it's not 100% lossless, more like 99% because it's encoded differently and it's still compressed, but it's made for listening to music.

posts.com: how to git gud at creating chord progressions on piano?

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com: become able to see what the intervals between the notes in the chord are, how they move in relation to each other to go to the next chord, which note of the next chord each of them ends up being, the melodies that they outline, which scales they imply and where the chord is in those scales.

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
>>114810662
Imitate performers you like, do it every day and transpose the key often. Say the functions out loud while playing. Soon enough you'll develop a feel for good progressions.

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
listen to songs you like and steal the good parts
after a while you will build up a repertoire of stolen hooks and will be able to smush them together into something of your own design
after a longer while you will begin to notice patterns in what you play, and you will mentally build a systemic picture of the layout of where you are in a song vis a vis diatonics

at any one time when I am playing a chord, I have a mental note of 3 or 4 other chords I could easily transition to next and what possibilities those would open up and whether it might start to change the key or not, and improvising is cutting your way through this endless infinite jungle of potentiality

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
Listened to pic related

Overall impression is that they're a competent stoner/psych/doom band (basically stoner but with some of the poppier Uncle Acid style - I can hear some QOTSA influence too I think) but they're a bit like Acid Mammoth in that they're playing all the right stuff but are kind of boring.

Elements in their favour are that their bass player is quite strong and has an interesting tone during the mini solos in 'All is Fine', though that song in particular runs out of steam half way through. The songs in general could be trimmed a bit imo, I'm not sure why 5-8mins is so normal for this genre - if you want people to groove you need to keep it tight.

'Electric Traveller', one of two singles from the album, starts strong but falls victim to this issue Aawks seem to have where they run out of gas mid-song and the groove grinds to a halt, then chugs along at half the pace for no reason. It does this weird tempo change a few times, kind of like the band had a few different ideas and duct-taped them together rather than making it sound coherent.

'Space City', the other single, is a bit tighter and has an interesting chorus with slightly dissonant vocals, but despite a relatively stable tempo it still sounds a bit disjointed and doesn't really spark much interest.

It's hard to put my finger on why I don't care for it exactly, it just sounds kind of stock and uninspired overall. It's like if I got an AI to generate a stoner/psych sound it would come out with this, in the same way that if I asked it to make generic stoner metal it would produce Acid Mammoth. By the end of the album it's hard to remember any song in particular, it all blends together because the overall sound is pretty uniform despite sections not always fitting together neatly.

It has a lot of the right elements for this type of music but is missing that secret ingredient that gets you hooked on the sound.

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
>>114804171
>But I still can't see how it can give you more "quality" except when you're resampling to another bit rate.
Depends on what you're talking about.

As far as distribution formats go, it's really in "best practices" territory rather than "this makes a really obvious difference". I read a pretty convincing analysis that suggested maybe 60 kHz at 20-22 bits would be fairly optimal for distribution. This gives good quality in the audible range without leaving a bunch of ultrasonic shit that can produce audible intermodulation products when distorted.
As far as DAWs go, it's extremely important to use higher quality. So it's typically 32 bit floating point, with 64 bit floating point used for IIR filtering, and internal oversampling for anything critical (distortion, compression, many kinds of synthesis, etc.). There are lots of creative ways to efficiently avoid aliasing, but sometimes you just have to do brute force oversampling.

>>114805055
>So I found this video which goes in depth about sample rates inside the DAW.
The takeaway is that if you run the DAW at 192 kHz and use distortion plugins or whatever, you're more likely to get intermodulation distortion and aliasing from parts of the signal that you can't hear anyway. The advantage of oversampling inside the plugins is that even if each plugin is internally oversampling by the same amount, it's better to reduce the bandwidth between the plugins.
>Um yeah, Nyquist says no.
It's so the anti-aliasing and reconstruction filters don't introduce phase shift or pre-echo in the audible range.
>Not only can most ears not hear anywhere near 20K anyhow
I think the measured upper limit is around 25 kHz
>Do you know what "mantissa" means?
Do you know what "scaling a signal by a very small coefficient and then scaling it back" means? See pic and consider the case where A = 0.0001. Pretty much all audio DSP is floating point now. Fixed point DSP is a pain in the ass and not any faster.

>The music for this aria was not composed by Vivaldi. The aria, originally called Sposa, non mi conosci, was taken from the Geminiano Giacomelli's opera La Merope (1734), composed before Vivaldi's pasticcio Bajazet. It was a common practice during Vivaldi's time to compile arias from other composers with one own's work for an opera. Vivaldi himself composed the arias for the good characters and mostly used existing arias from other composers for the villains in this opera.

It makes a lot more sense when you consider maybe 90% of people don’t actually “listen” to music. It’s engaged with usually for some social or other reason. I’ve never met a person who listens to Bad Bunny that would be capable of articulating what they enjoy about his music. I’m not a snob about what people listen to, even if I consider it garbage, but I think people ought to be able to justify what they choose to occupy their time with. Otherwise it’s not selected, it’s clung to out of an ignorance of the wealth of other things that they would enjoy better, like a perpetual child still afraid to eat vegetables. People mainly listen to bad pop artists because they haven’t tried listening to anything else, so the success of many pop artists is propagated by people who care little about music. The other examples you provided are a bit different, because they’ve been reevaluated through the passage of time. That’s why Bad Bunny’s music seems to have no cultural impact. Not only is it uninteresting on its own but the listeners are disinterested, more than they know. Basically music is just an obnoxious alternative to silence for people who don’t know better.

Kid A and Amnesiac are head and shoulders above the rest. 1998-2000 was Radiohead’s one creative period. Everything before that was just leading up to it, and everything since has been trying (and failing) to avoid retread.

Of the two, I used to like Kid A better when I was in high school and was a big Radiohead fan. As an adult, I’m far less interested in the band, but Amnesiac has emerged as the clear winner. The songs on Kid A that everybody points to as the best (How to Disappear Completely, Motion Picture Soundtrack) are actually the weakest and sappiest songs there and really drag the album down after dozens of listens. The tracks that serve the same purpose on Amnesiac (Pyramid Song and Life in a Glasshouse) are far better.

fuck it. I've got time to kill, so here's my personal ranking of all eight radiohead studio albums, worst to best.

Pablo honey: THE album. Not much to say that hasn’t already been memed to death. It’s a solid indie rock album but not really an RH album. Everyone likes Creep, but my personal pick from the album is definitely Blow out.

The king of limbs: my first listen of the studio version of this album remains one of the strangest experiences of my life. I’m not really sure how to explain anything on this album. The instrumentation is incredibly experimental, but execution is at times lacking, and the album needs support from vocal performances and lyricism. The live version of this album is amazing, however. I’d place that version of this album somewhere around Amnesiac.

The bends: a classic indie rock album from the 90s. Possesses Yorke’s signature pessimistic lyricism, but lacks any of their later experimentalism. Not bad, just forgettable, although fake plastic trees and street spirit are admittedly fantastic.
In rainbows: incredibly overrated. The majority of this album is bland and lyrically uninspired. I really only come back for Weird Fishes and All I Need; I suppose 15 step is alright as well.

Hail to the thief: though it’s the only RH album that explicitly revolves around left-wing politics, it’s ironically arguably their most optimistic album. Still, Yorke works best with abstract topics, and this album’s overt theming seems to weaken his songwriting throughout most of the album. Sonically, RH cling to their newfound experimentalism while reaching for their indie rock roots, making this album sound like the reciprocal of OK computer. Salvaged by the inclusion of 2+2=5, Sit down stand up, and there there.

posts.name: continued...
posts.com:
>>114805439
Amnesiac: perhaps the most inconsistent out of all RH’s albums. Includes some of their best songs, like Knives Out and Glasshouse, while also containing their worst tracks, such as Hunting Bears and that awful Morning Bell remix. Instrumentally, RH venture into abstract experimentation light-years further than what they had accomplished on Kid A. Lyrically, rivals A moon shaped pool in its pessimism, though unlike AMSP Yorke rarely succumbs to nihilism. The bizarre instrumentation and utterly depressing lyricism combine to make an album that literally sounds like the act of suicide. Favorite track is Life in a Glasshouse.

A moon shaped pool: It’s blonde, but made by British people. Calming and gorgeously nocturnal in its sound, yet lyrically the most pessimistic of all RH’s works. Encompasses topics from painful breakups to the afterlife with a consistently nihilistic, yet somehow not at all edgy mindset. Its duds are outweighed by some of RH’s best instrumentation and lyrics on Daydreaming and Present Tense, respectively.

OK computer: the perfect rock album. Arguably more consistent than Kid A, but lacks the experimental sounds that made the latter so unique and memorable. Still a biting critique of dystopian, late-stage capitalism delivered through wit (compare the brute shrieking of RATM) over addictive guitar riffs. Favorite track is definitely The Tourist, with Lucky and Paranoid Android tying for second place.

Kid A: the perfect album. Usually my 10s have two or three songs that leave me floored but here all but one track (optimistic) blows my fucking mind. It’s near impossible to pick favorite tracks from here but, out of the 11 (yes, including untitled) phenomenal tracks, how to disappear completely felt like floating through otherworldly clouds, and in limbo haunts the listener with its deafening screams of paranoia and visions of decay.

I like Hail to the Thief the most. There's something to be said about its fast and loose turnaround which resulted in a fast and loose album with some of the band's wildest performances, but ultimately it's the very solemn, autumnal tone of the album that does it for me. Earlier in the thread it was stated that this was their most optimistic record, but I personally think it's their bleakest (and if anything, I think King of Limbs is their most optimistic). I listen to songs like Backdrifts, We Suck Young Blood, Wolf At The Door, Sit Down, Stand Up, 2+2=5 and There There and hear nothing but abject pessimism and defeatism. Sail to the Moon is vaguely optimistic but to me, this is a record that starts in deep shit and ends in even deeper shit. For as unrefined as it objectively is, I'm actually fine with that and greatly enjoy the tone of this record for what it is.

>>114806887
Kid A's my next favorite and despite generally being perceived as a holistic piece, I would readily cite the first 4 songs as one massive highlight reel. If anything, I'd almost say the album is frontloaded - I don't enjoy the likes of Idioteque and MPS quite as much as everyone else seems to in isolation but again, they work within the whole. Kid A's the album to take in "as an album" moreso than the rest.

My favourite Radiohead album is Kid A, and I think it’s their best album too. Everything from the album cover, to the drum fill at the end of Optimistic - perfect album. There’s no other album I’ve heard that captures what I love about music 100%, except this one. It’s a beautiful album.

But OK Computer is *just* behind it. I wouldn’t disagree with anyone who says that OK Computer was the best Radiohead album. Airbag, Paranoid Android, Subterranean Homesick Alien, Exit Music, Let Down, Karma Police, Climbing Up The Walls, No Surprises, Lucky, The Tourist. All amazing tracks - on one album. Electioneering is a weak spot but still a pretty good track. Amazing album.

I can understand saying In Rainbows is the best Radiohead album but I don’t think it reaches Kid A or OK Computer’s highs. All great tracks, especially Nude, Weird Fishes, Faust Arp, Reckoner, Jigsaw, Videotape. Some of the band’s best.

The Bends is a great album but with a weak spot or two, like High & Dry and Bones. Both are good tracks, just noticeably less quality than the rest. Planet Telex, Fake Plastic Trees, (Nice Dream), Just, My Iron Lung, Bullet Proof, Black Star, Sulk, Street Spirit. Classic tracks. Bullet Proof and Nice Dream are two of my favourite Radiohead tracks.

I love The King of Limbs. I don’t think it reaches the individual track quality of OK Computer or Kid A but it’s such a cohesive album experience and the atmosphere they build on it is so defined. It’s the most relistenable Radiohead album outside of Kid A, in my opinion. It’s such a well-crafted album and the tracks segue so well. If OK Computer and Kid A didn’t exist, The King of Limbs might be my favourite Radiohead album.

A Moon Shaped Pool is in a similar boat to The King of Limbs. I can totally get why someone might say this is their best. It’s a gorgeous album. Year by year it gets better. Present Tense, Tinker Tailor, True Love Waits is such an amazing album-closing sequence.

posts.com:
Personally, I have to say that I never had much time for King Crimson. I disliked their first album and, apart from a track here and there, didn't find much I cared for on later albums either. To make things harder, they were contemporaries of Henry Cow and we were often pointlessly compared with them (especially Fred Frith who got foolishly compared/confused with Robert Fripp). But we never saw the connection really; they were working in a much narrower musical field than we were. And when they began to make big statements about their originality for improvising (around Jaimie Muir/Larks Tongues time) we found that frankly rather pathetic. But that was their way - after all Fripp claimed to have invented 'frippertronics', which is either a mark of ignorance on his part or outrageous arrogance, since every guitarist 'invented' that obvious procedure. I was not a fan of the other groups you list either, or Yes or Genesis for that matter, the quintessential 'progressive' groups. I don't think we had much in common with any of them. We certainly didn't learn anything from them. I, for instance, would have to go back to early Zappa, Beefheart, Barrett's Pink Floyd, Soft Machine, AMM, Sun Ra, Coltrane, Coleman, Stockhausen, Schoenberg and so on for influences. And for contemporary bands in the 70's, Magma, Faust, Samla Mammas Manna.

-Chris Cutler

>>114788022
A triad is the root-3rd-5th of a chord, it gives you the sound and feel of a chord. A C major triad sounds good over a C major chord. A C minor triad sounds good over a C minor chord. The only difference is the 3rd, which defines whether a chord is major or minor. When you know the major and minor triads, you can use them to play a chord progression and add some flavor with the 3rd & 5th rather than just chugging on the root note like a pleb. But you need to know where the root notes are on your bass so you know where to move your fingers to play a chord/triad.

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=T0dr3rH7zxI

This video might help idk I didn't watch the whole thing, but it's pretty simple once you understand it.

As for your bass, make sure the volume is up on your instrument as well as the amp. Check for wear on your cable and test with a different instrument if you can.

An unfortunate thing with tutorials is that, the more obscure/niche the thing you're wanting a tutorial on, the less likely it is that there will be one. I listened to a couple songs and I'd say.. Your best bet will probably be a combination of looking into beginner "ear training", and then perhaps finding some tutorials on songs by comparable, more popular artists that you like so you can pick up the technical skills to eventually learn Unwound songs by ear. Once you can say "yeah, I can play a few songs that sound about as difficult as this" you can pick some songs where the bass is easy to hear and just start matching what the bass player is doing. Slow the song down to 65-75% speed if you need to. If you're finding *good*, accurate covers you might also be able to sort of cheat a little and copy what the person in the cover is doing since they'll be a lot more prominent in the mix, and you can see their fingers.
